Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth U.S. president in history.
The diploma, medal and check of $1.4 million will be given, among other things, for the outstanding effort in strengthening global diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The White House chief and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and will have a lot to do.
First, a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the committee that elected him in October from among 172 people and 33 organizations.
Then, the presidential couple are scheduled to meet with the King of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate with a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive it, though the third to do so in office.
The White House has already announced that upon receiving the award, he will speak about the war in Afghanistan.
The President does not want to avoid that subject, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war effort was further increased by the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which he does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, the diploma and the check for ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
He's proposing to donate the paraffins to charity, but he hasn't decided yet which organization specifically.
During the entire program, the President and his wife will attend a banquet attended by the Norwegian kings, the prime minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude toward the award.
He mentioned, for example, feeling that he did not deserve it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not just for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action".
