USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest man in the world, as a diligent student, repeats the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, whom he himself considered the most foolish.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it turned out to be a copy of the script Bush used for Iraq, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase "just like in Iraq" used several times in the same text, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement for his own statement: "A new way forward".
It was he himself who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country suffering from civil war, and criticized it as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences".
The following months, however, proved that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only one possible and successful, so that today Iraq is not mentioned in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, but he left his successor in a much more favourable starting position than might have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will be repeated.
Field captains again urged him to increase the military contingent, most notably the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal. He, even in spite of traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He called for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he tricked the general into thinking about 10,000 soldiers.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he had at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama's entire strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this process in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will produce the same results as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders abiding by agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is being kept.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the head every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, though formally established, will remain only a Potemkin people.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated because of the confused relationships, further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "action-capable", a minimum objective of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is clashing with his volunteerism.
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and now it is on the verge of exploding.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war so that they "come home soon" will do some miracle here.
From the political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor which can radically affect the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: whether to try to solve the problem with military force or not.
The answers will need to be sought precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will mean a dramatic reversal for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential elections and therefore there is still plenty of time to find another strategy, if this one turns out to be a total failure.
