France is also preparing similar measures.
This year women received the Nobel Prizes in all categories except physics
A record number of five women received this year's Nobel Prizes in specialised categories and literature from King Charles XVI Gustav of Sweden in Stockholm.
In addition to the four scientists, a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller, was among the winners.
The Nobel Prize in medicine was awarded to two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as their compatriot Jack Szostak for their research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to the Israeli Ada Jonath and the Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for their explanation of the structure and function of ribosomes.
The last prize awarded, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was given to the American Elinor Ostrom and her compatriot Oliver Williamson for their analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without a woman winner, was Physics.
This prize was awarded today to the scientists Charles Kao for their research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith and Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which forms the basis of all digital cameras, faxes and telescopes.
Each prize winner picked up his diploma, Nobel medal and certificate of the money received.
This amount in each category is up to SEK 10 million (approximately SEK 25 million).
If there are several winners in each category, the prize is shared amongst them.
