The secret of Norway's splendor solved: the Russians tested a missile
A special light effect of unknown origin was observed over Norway.
The Russian Defense Ministry finally admitted yesterday that near the borders with Norway it tested an intercontinental ballistic missile.
The launch failed again. The "Bulava" missile, once intended to be the pride of the Russian military, is becoming the nightmare of Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Even their repeated presence in missile tests has not had the desired effect on the success of test flights.
Bulava, in most cases, did not fly out or there was a failure in the air.
In the Russian newspapers they write of "Bulava" as "a missile that does not fly".
A missile that doesn't fly, but shines.
During this, the 13th test, no problems occurred at first.
At the end of the flight, technical problems occurred again.
The engine probably exploded in the third stage of the missile.
This time "Bulava" was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donskoy, which was floating submerged in the White Sea.
This type of missile allows the launch from a moving vessel that is submerged at the same time.
So it's likely that the mysterious light over Norway, caused by an unidentified flying object, was actually the failed "Bulava".
The Norwegians were equally at first not hesitant that it was a Russian missile.
The generals this time defend themselves by saying that we cannot simply talk about failure.
The first two stages of the missile held and the failure occurred in the third.
In the previous cases the engines broke down immediately at the first stage.
Although none of the launches went completely error-free, according to the Ministry of Defence management only six of the thirteen failed.
The success of almost fifty percent is full of optimism for the generals and that is why they continue to affirm that "Bulavá" will one day fly without problems and that it will even manage to carry up to ten hypersonic nuclear blocks, whose total maximum weight is 1.15 tons.
