Czech discovery: a substance that works even on 'calcified' HIV viruses
Czech and German team of scientists test new compounds that can moderate the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective on a common variant of the virus as some drugs already available.
AIDS is not curable until now.
However, a combination of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body can significantly prolong the lives of patients.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, medicines no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of overcoming the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarbons have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metallic carbonates are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that's different from all the drugs used today, and so they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, "improved" compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to the albumin of the virus.
Metalocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitorous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, no HIV fractionation would occur and no mature, infectious virus corpuscles would be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, explain scientists in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In an article published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which is still being systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
Testing of the effect of this series of substances against HIV proteases was carried out in test tubes, and also against their resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
