This year volunteers placed more than 16,000 crowns in the graves of Arlington Cemetery, areas in the Pentagon, graves at Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, Battery Park in New York City and at the United Airlines Flight 93 memorial site in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
By the second year, the Walmart Foundation had donated more than $150,000 to buy and transport the crowns.
Charleen Hunt, 70, of Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in honor of her late husband, a career military man.
As long as her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said this was her way of giving a reward to those who made sacrifices.
This is a modest way that civilians can support our troops, he said.
It's like visiting a family grave.
Wrapped in layers of warm clothing, the volunteers walked through the cemetery's broad meadows and hills.
Volunteers headed to older World War I, World War II, and Vietnam war graves, because they don't get as many visitors as the new graves, organizers said.
The atmosphere was cheerful as the children played and the couples held hands, while they carried the fresh pine to the tombstones.
Each circular crown was a deep green, with a small red knot tied at the top.
Nearby, Section 60, where most of the Iraq and Afghanistan war veterans are buried, was virtually silenced.
