Cuban officials arrested a U.S. government contractor
The Cuban government has arrested a U.S. government contractor who distributed mobile phones and laptops in the country, State Department officials said Saturday.
The contractor, who has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda.
The company works on projects for clients such as the United States Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
Consular officers along with the U.S. Interests Section in Havana are seeking access to the detainee, who was arrested on December 5.
Specific charges have not been made public, although under Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything deemed "dangerous".
All so-called counterrevolutionary activities, including light protests and critical writings, carry the risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and speeches are considered serious crimes.
Cuba has a nascent blogger community, led by popular commentator Yoani Sánchez, who often writes about how she and her husband are followed and harassed by government agents.
Sánchez has requested permission to leave the country to accept awards on several occasions, but the permission has been denied.
The arrest of an American contractor may likely spark tensions between the Castro brothers' communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which has been seeking a "slow-paced" approach to improve relations with the island.
The New York Times was the first to break the news of the arrest on Friday night.
The new US policy emphasizes that if the Cuban government takes concrete measures, such as releasing political prisoners and creating more space for the opposition, there will be reciprocity on the part of the United States.
Mobile phones and laptops are legal in Cuba, even though they are new and coveted products in a country where the average salary of a government worker is $15 a month.
The Cuban government granted ordinary citizens the right to buy mobile phones only this year; they are mostly used for texting, as a 15-minute phone conversation would cost a daily wage.
Internet use is extremely limited on the island.
It is available in expensive hotels and for foreign hotel guests, and in some government establishments, such as universities.
Cubans who want to connect, often have to give their names to the government.
Access to many Web sites is restricted.
The arrest of an American in Cuba is unusual.
Gloria Berbena, press officer at the U.S. Interests Section in Havana, said that most of the handful of U.S. citizens in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes like drug trafficking.
Berbena said he couldn't provide any more information about the arrest.
