In an ageing China, a change of course
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters that preached to them about the fact that "Mother Earth is too tired to support more children" and "one more baby means one more grave".
They learned the lesson so well that when Shanghai government officials, alarmed by the low birth rate and aging population of their city, suddenly changed course this summer and began encouraging young couples to have more than one child, their reaction was instant and firm: No way.
We've already given all our time and energy for just one child.
We have nothing left for a second, said Wang, 31, a human resources manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, creating two generations of notoriously stubborn, misbehaved one-children, affectionately nicknamed "little emperors", a demographic crisis is emerging in the country.
The average birth rate has plummeted to 1.8 children per couple, compared with six when the policy became effective, according to the Division of Child Development.
The number of residents aged 60 and over is projected to explode from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent by 2050, well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is worse in rich coastal cities with highly educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for nearly 22 percent of Shanghai's registered residents, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai Municipal Family Planning and Population Commission, said that fertile couples should have babies to "help reduce the proportion of the aging population and mitigate future labor shortages".
Shanghai is about to be "as old (not as rich, though) as developed countries like Japan and Sweden", he said.
Gradual relief
Drafted into the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is possibly the most controversial mandate introduced to date by the Communist Party.
Couples who violate the policy face huge fines, up to three times their annual salary in some areas, and employment discrimination.
Chinese officials have endorsed the policy for its contribution to avoiding critical pressure on its natural resources, while human rights defenders have denounced abuses in the policy's enforcement.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to have abortions.
In addition, many couples have had abortions based on the sex of the fetus, leading to an unnaturally high male-female ratio.
In recent years, demographic officials have gradually softened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities, and cases in which both the husband and wife are only children, and in 2007 they toned down many of their hard-line slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Beijing University Institute of Demographic Research, said that central government officials have recently been debating even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is an only child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost overnight, the signs that ordered families to have one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be eligible to have a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples at their homes and to slide leaflets under the doors.
It has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say the response has been very unobtrusive.
Disappointing Answer
While officials in a rural town outside Shanghai maintain that they saw a moderate increase in requests from couples wanting a second child after the campaign was launched, more urban districts indicate no change.
Huinan Municipality, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
