UN group outlines plan to cut emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, so far characterized by challenging stances and mutual recriminations, caught renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
The text, prepared by an ad hoc UN task force, does not discuss how much money rich countries would give to poor countries to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how the developed economies and the major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of global temperature rise that policy makers would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture".
It shows the profile for a possible agreement, in which the industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries would cut their emissions over the same period by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also stepped up talks on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday was the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the talks last week.
US climate envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emissions cuts for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary cuts by major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, compared to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make a deal without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also lamented that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei claimed that the top US climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the US would not help China economically to deal with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and the emerging economies.
The battle is as much about saving individual economies as it is about saving the planet, with China and the United States clashing over their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the world's 24 most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the boldest action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that major powers are arguing over who should pay for the costs of limiting greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to contain the big emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who also works as a regional adviser on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the main participants say that the talks will produce at most a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push by small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process", in part because they are now unified and demanding action from emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before the heads of government can reach a deal.
High-level officials, including Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice Minister, got off the planes and rushed to the Bella Center hallways, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, to be able to delimit the claims that will be arbitrated over the next week.
The sheer disorder of the meeting - where 13,000 people come and go from the convention center each day, activists playing guitar present nightly shows mocking countries they say are selling out, and preliminary proposals are passed from hand to hand instead of via mail - poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all the key ministers are here at the moment, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We're entering the big leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
