Management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a matter of employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was a matter of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the centre of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to strategies for market conquest... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to the factors of customer preference is regularly repeated.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all intellectual functions of the enterprise, especially R & D and, even more so, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) "requires all parties involved (...) to have proactive behaviour and a forward-looking view"; it requires a commitment from employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of authoritarian management.
We therefore call for a management revolution, which would be to put employees at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls are of relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the Orange questionnaire among its employees, incite the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not at all.
- In principle, because I could verify that, faced with a new situation, and after many twists and turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Because they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old behaviorist theory that American "neuroscience" recently revived, and which the Institutes of Study and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management posture, unsuited to today's world.
Identifying and measuring mobilisation factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the smooth running of modern enterprises requires adopting a finalist view of human behaviour.
It is about integrating into all business management thinking and practice a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of making their dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Today, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring the mobilising factors, business managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their 'social performance' and relocate human resource management 'into place'.
In this way, they create a favourable terrain for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: Obama receives praise from the right for "just war"
This Friday, the American right, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the concept of "just war" against America's enemies, hailed Obama's speech on Thursday.
Conservatives, who had discredited the awarding of the award to Obama on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 election.
I loved what she said, said Mrs. Palin, a leading figure in the right wing of the Republican party, to the newspaper USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the subject of war "sometimes necessary" in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is certainly the last thing the Americans want to be forced to do, but it is necessary.
Terrorists must be stopped, he observed.
Obama, who inherited his predecessor George W. Bush's two wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, devoted himself on Thursday in Oslo to justifying the use of force, a way of explaining his decision to send 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama opponent, Newt Gingrich, considered that the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really very good, the former Speaker of the House of Representatives was pleased, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential words.
At times, the speech seemed very historic, Gingrich declared during an interview on the radio program "The Takeaway".
The former elected representative, who some consider a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, was pleased to hear "a leftist president" when he reminded the members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free nor could they give a peace prize if the recourse to force did not exist".
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush's speeches and current columnist for the Washington Post, Obama delivered "a very American speech".
In addition to presenting himself as a "citizen of the world", as he "always does", he "spoke like a North American president" by reminding Europeans "that they live in a security bubble that they did not create and that they do not do much to preserve it", Gerson said.
Among the few on the right who are not so convinced, a Bush-era hawk, former UN ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "monotonous, pretentious and uninspired" on the National Review Online website.
To the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover war with the notion of justice, it's easy to justify the massacre of innocents, he warned.
However, the center-left press praised the president.
Los Angeles Time, while still believing Obama received the Nobel prematurely, called his speech "superproduction" especially for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech "should serve as a roadmap for guiding international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression", the Californian newspaper enthusiastically noted.
Obama "made the speech that was needed", the New York Times estimated, judging it "both bleak and uplifting".
Road transport: three marathon negotiations to guarantee Christmas supplies
After three marathon negotiations, the unions in the road sector and the TLF (Transport and Logistics of France), the only employer organisation to remain until the end, reached an agreement on Friday afternoon that puts an end to the strike slogan and the threat to Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday night, Transport Secretary Dominique Bussereau "rejoiced" over the agreement, following several negotiating sessions that began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators left at dawn on Friday in the hope of quickly signing the text of the agreement by late in the morning.
Even though three employers' organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) withdrew by knocking on the door.
But a meeting of more than six hours, which began at 11 a.m., was necessary to get everyone to agree and the text to be signed at 6 p.m.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to businesses" and "was feared to disrupt the holidays", Bussereau said.
The text provides for a 4% increase for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport) and a 2.9% increase for the highest wages (in international transport).
The hourly rate rises from 8.72 euros to 9.06 for low-wage workers.
It's not much, but we started with a big disadvantage, Patrice Clos (FO) explained.
If so, we will give the order to our militants that there be no more cuts or blockades at the supply centers.
But there can always be some disgruntled rebel, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, acknowledged that it was "a good deal", although it was "difficult to grant increases to high wages in view of international competition".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros per month for the lowest salaries and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is a common-sense agreement that respects employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) recognised it as "a historic agreement".
The Commission is also proposing a new directive on the protection of workers from the risks of exposure to radioactive substances.
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel expenses and for the holding of general road transport assemblies in the first half of 2010, which will allow, in particular, to address the issue of an extraordinary payment and the modernisation of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled that "a reduction of 100 million euros in employer charges" was the subject of a government amendment to the 2009 rectification finance bill, which the National Assembly voted on Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "under the same terms".
The signing of TLF allows the agreement to apply, firstly, to the companies affiliated to this organisation and, secondly, to the whole profession, should the Minister of Labour extend it.
It will be done "as soon as possible", Bussereau said.
Opposition from employers' organisations could only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced it as a "naïve business", as the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the CO2 tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate in an emergency situation, not as a conclusion to an analysis discussed by the parties, but not to upset those who wish to eat turkey at the next Christmas dinner, the Unostra lamented.
The OECD said the agreement "put at risk the stability of many SMEs in the sector over the next 12 months".
