Turkish justice dissolves the prokurdo party, a decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday in favour of the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately provoked angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could make it much more difficult for the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that harmed the independence of the State and its indivisible unity", the court president, Hasim Kiliç, told the press after four days of deliberations.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a majority of seven votes was needed to obtain the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's leaders, including its president Ahmet Türk and deputy Aysel Tugluk, are barred from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the termination of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that the deputies would leave Parliament before becoming parliamentarians without party label.
The decision follows a 2007 proceeding by the Supreme Court prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP of following the "principles" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many other countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party claims it has no "organic links" with the PKK, but refuses to classify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court's verdict comes at a time when the government is reaching out to the Kurdish community with a series of measures to strengthen their rights, so that the Kurds can stop supporting the PKK and thus end the conflict.
DTP leaders claimed that a dissolution could generate a resurgence of tensions in Southeastern Anatolia, where a large number of demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan degenerated into clashes with police over the past weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of protesters have gathered outside the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the large city in the southeast populated mostly by Kurds.
Law enforcement threw tear gas and water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or stones with slingshots.
In Istanbul, about a hundred people also gathered.
Following the verdict, Türk said the court's decision would "deepen discouragement".
Turkey cannot solve this issue (Kurdish, NDLR) by dissolving a party, he told the press.
The government, which is made up of a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
We are opposed to the closure of parties.
This is not a solution, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic opening launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can of course expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
This Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
