The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-meter-long, 1.50-meter-high animal that ran on its two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this wouldn't have been anything special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily features, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It tells us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in 2006 at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we've found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they collected the remains of five specimens in total.
A discovery confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt says it is an exceptional find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments".
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current view, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the sauries were divided into their three most important lineages: carnivorous theropods including Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long-necked" and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (saurians with bird pelvis), to which, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus belong.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt comments.
For example, in the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of air sacs, like those possessed by the descendants of theropods, the birds.
Thanks to air sacs, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In the case of Tawa hallae the bones of the spine were also evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive air-bag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related lineage of later giant sauropods also possessed air sacs and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the earliest dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, researchers infer that the saurians first appeared there.
Thus, the three lineages were separated at first and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single landmass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa hallae the remains of two other theropods not closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three waves of migration into North America occurred, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the Science study.
Naturally, there are opponents too.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Your opinion may give a distorted picture, for in South America alone many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral lineage of reptiles to the dominant land vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains a mystery.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosaurs and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the Triassic-Jurassic boundary.
Success stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, comments Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories don't always last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact halted the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and had since led a miserable existence: the mammals.
