New Silicon Valley
For many years, it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was in the Soviet Union a heavily guarded site for secret weapons research.
Today, the community of 216,000, located 23 miles [37 km] from central Moscow, is considered the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Important research and production centres for micro and nanoelectronics are located here.
Since September 2008, representatives from Selenograd have been in contact with the scientific headquarters of Riedberg in Frankfurt, with the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
The European Union and the Member States have agreed to the agreement on the establishment of a European Union.
The Russian delegation was led by Moscow's Vice-Mayor Yuri Rosljak and Selangrad's Mayor Anatoly Smirnov; the head of planning services Edwin Schwarz signed for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of the FIZ and directors of small and medium-sized enterprises of the Natural Sciences Research Centre will travel to a seminar in Selenogrado.
Scientific exchange
It is a continuous scientific exchange.
But it also addresses business relations.
The FIZ companies will have the opportunity to enter the growing Russian market.
In return, Russian scientific companies want to have access to contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is home to important Russian companies and research institutes.
These include, for example, the Moscow Institute of Electronic Technology, the large consortia Sitronics and Rossijskaja Elektronika.
The community was founded in 1958 as the so-called "Socialist Planning City" for weapons research.
Selenogrado (literally translated as "Green City") got its name from the forested mountain landscape, in which research facilities were settled.
Brakes of Stuttgart
The Stuttgart Dimension 21 is not placed high enough for anything.
For the proponents of the project, it is simply "the new heart of Europe".
The law is much more than the reduction of a railway station, much more than a monstrous construction project, which will precipitate a decade of hopeless construction site chaos in the capital of the Banden-Württemberg region.
Stuttgart 21 emerged from the spirit of the 1980s.
Terminals with rails, which end in the middle of the city, were considered at the time to be 19th-century engineering fossils, acting as brakes on modern rail traffic, since in the past it took a huge amount of time to hook up the locomotives from behind forward.
Roll, dry stop, continue the journey, but that's the way it's got to be.
And that's why the terminals had to disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: a transit station, which is about halfway along the transEuropean lines between Paris and Budapest/Bratislava; hence the slogan 'Heart of Europe'.
S21 will really be initiated, even though the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious designers have known that in the Hessian and Bavarian capitals it is almost priceless to implement reduction.
The railway terminals of course also have no more problems of entry and exit, since there are reversible locomotives with a tractor unit and driver's car at both ends.
However: Stuttgart 21 including the new ICE constructed section to Ulm will already be started.
Federal and local politicians have arranged it that way.
The railway continues, also because the risks of the major individual infrastructure projects of the Republic are borne by the taxpayer and not the State.
From the urban point of view, the project is still justified to a certain extent.
New urban space is created, with many green areas, probably from the designer's computer-generated graphics.
For the rail transport system S21 is harmful.
The crossing station and road support are designed for passenger transport, which was attributed to the enormous growth typical of the 1980s.
At that time there was no competition for low-cost flights.
But modern transport policy must first focus on strengthening freight transport, since rail transport is considerably greener than that carried out by trucks on roads.
However, the new sections under construction are good for freight trains because of the steep gradients.
Even more serious is the fact that S21 also indirectly affects many other railway projects.
More than six billion euros must be buried in the Zuavos.
That's the official figure.
Experts consider it more realistic between 10 and 15 billion.
It is certain that in the next decade money will be lacking at other crossings and narrow passages in the network.
A total of 60 major projects are on the list of the Ministry of Transport.
One of the most important is the extension of more than 180 kilometres of long rails across the Rhine valley.
Since 1987 the track has been built at a slow pace.
It would be urgent here to step on the accelerator properly.
However, the S21 acts as a brake.
The Rhine Valley will be the bottleneck for international freight transport: through the heart of Europe.
