Dreaming worlds
In the waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only the mentally ill and the drug addicts who are losing the line between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can unrestrainedly indulge in the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, one who experiences sleep-like states during waking, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world to be a lunatic or a drug addict, or at least a maniac.
But such images and voices do not just come from the mentally ill or the drug addicts.
It's our imagination that's to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes blur the lines between dream, madness, and reality.
Dream-modified states of consciousness can appear in a variety of ways, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, similar processes can be referred to as the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, states of shamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain - especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - has been upset and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts often occur.
Gravity has no power over him anymore.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived of hallucinations as a form of waking sleep, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness to the dream states", for Sigmund Freud, sleep was even "a psychosis, with all its mispurposes, mad formations, and mirages".
