Hallucinations are a cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time the affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the inside, and they fall into a state of overexcitation that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecutory mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatry clinic at the Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time he enters into a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot organize them actively.
That's why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
It's generally not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in your life
Unlike in a dream, says Fuchs, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is".
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are grounded in reality, the distancing of experience takes place in reality.
For researchers, why our brains are so wild is still an unknown.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can cause anyone to temporarily lose touch with reality.
But not everyone develops a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that other factors besides genes are also involved.
Researchers believe that the victims suffered minimal brain damage.
We suspect that brain neuronal maturity is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also goes unnoticed for many years, remains a mystery.
Environmental influences also play an important role. Stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a predisposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, since they interfere with the brain's transmission system.
