Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The unreal world in our head), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, alongside psychological disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depression, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and traumatic brain injury.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also experience hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain where sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or are uncoerced; when our brains get hot, but also when there is a lack of stimulation.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
