The borderline between sleep and hallucination
In this world too focused on the conscious, imaginary experiences tend to become pathological, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative. Madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated what is called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person experiencing them considers real and that later on cannot distinguish from waking.
Dream states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or illness, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened with a loss of self or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, this replaces a very dangerous real situation with a self and imaginary world that is decoupled from reality.
A form of borderline situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a change of world occurs, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an intolerable situation in itself that our own creative capacity allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
