75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generations who want to become mothers.
This is the finding of the study 'Fertility and the career of women in Spain', carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers have had limited opportunities in the workplace because of motherhood.
The study shows that there are many differences in the start of cohabitation and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they do.
Women who have no activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start living together earlier, have their first child earlier, and have more children.
In contrast, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are delaying cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer children.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting a relationship, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time in their life to get them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed has a great influence on maternity, although less on the timing of mating", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women at marriage and at the time of the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which they marry and have their first child.
The difference also remains between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with primary and secondary education have become mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 respectively on average.
"Another division is also established between women according to their level of education.
While those with elementary education get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child", Delgado details.
