Emergency braking assistance is now compulsory
As with ABS anti-lock braking and will be the case with ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already available on all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while a period of absence is fixed for the rest until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's measure aims to increase pedestrian protection, but because of its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by range.
The emergency brake assistant increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects by the driver's push-pull.
But he doesn't always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not hit the brake before the collision and half of them had not used all their power.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The aid intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum from the braking system, reducing the distance the car takes to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were fitted with these types of components, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents involving human injury would be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In the event of failure to react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device applies maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
